aS"Just before Monday's session began, the judge issued a series of rulings that will allow Jackson expert witnesses to testify but limit some of their opinions."
p809
aS"The lawsuit seeks a judgment against AEG Live equal to the money Jackson would have earned over the course of his remaining lifetime if he had not died in 2009. Jackson lawyers denied media reports that they were seeking $40 billion in damages if AEG Live is found liable, but it could cost the company several billion dollars, according to estimates of Jackson's income potential."
p810
aS'AEG Live is a subsidiary of AEG, a global entertainment company that was up for sale recently with an $8 billion asking price.'
p811
aS"Palazuelos reversed an earlier tentative decision Monday that would have limited the amount of damages the Jacksons could argue AEG should pay if found liable in the singer's death. \xc2\xa0The decision raises the potential damages by about $1 billion."
p812
aS'One of the Jacksons\' experts, certified public accountant Arthur Erk, estimated that Michael Jackson could have earned $1.4 billion by taking his "This Is It" tour around the world for 260 shows. AEG executives discussed extending the tour beyond the 50 shows scheduled for London, Jackson lawyers said.'
p813
aS'Jackson lawyer Perry Sanders, in arguing for the judge to allow Erk\'s testimony, said when "This Is It" tickets went on sale in March 2009, there was the "highest demand to see anyone in the history of the world. No one has ever come close."'
p814
aS'"There was so much demand, they filled 2 million seats in hours," Sanders said, quoting an e-mail from AEG Live CEO Randy Phillips sent to AEG\'s owner.'
p815
aS'"We would have had to do 100-plus shows to fill the demand" in London, he said Phillips wrote. Jackson could have packed the Tokyo Dome several times in a world tour, he said.'
p816
aS'But AEG lawyer Sabrina Strong called it "very speculative" that Jackson would have even finished the 50 London shows before dying.'
p817
aS'AEG lawyers argued that Jackson didn\'t perform 260 shows and make that much money even in his prime. "He never came anywhere close to that," Strong said. "No one other than Cher has ever done that."'
p818
aS'Erk also calculated Jackson would have followed with four more world tours before he turned 65.'
p819
aS'Palazuelos weighed in during a hearing on Thursday, noting that the Rolling Stones are still touring into their 70s.'
p820
